    id: "c-rmc1-03",
    title: "Sixty-Four Squares of Myself: A Memoir Reviewed",
    text: "There is a moment two-thirds of the way through Vera Kalman's memoir 'Zugzwang' when the book stops being about chess and reveals what it has been about all along. Kalman, then nineteen and ranked among the top junior players in Europe, resigns a winnable position against a rival she despises, walks out of the tournament hall in Budapest, and does not touch a piece for eleven years. Most sporting memoirs would treat this as the wound around which a redemption arc is organised. Kalman treats it as a liberation whose cost she is still auditing, and the refusal of that easy shape is what lifts this book above the crowded shelf it might otherwise have joined.\n\nThe early chapters cover ground that will be familiar to anyone who has read about prodigies: the parent, in this case a father, who discovers his daughter's gift and reorganises the household around it; the narrowing of childhood into preparation; the strange doubleness of being celebrated for something you are no longer sure you chose. Kalman writes about this without the score-settling bitterness that curdles so many such accounts, which is not to say she lets her father off. Her method is colder and more effective. She simply describes: the notebook in which he logged her mistakes, the holidays that were tournaments, the birthday spent analysing a lost endgame. The reader is left to do the condemning, and does.\n\nWhere the book genuinely surprises is in its treatment of the game itself. Chess writing for a general audience tends to oscillate between mystification, all genius and madness, and tedious technicality. Kalman finds a third register. She is superb on what competition does to perception: the way a tournament hall's silence has textures, the way an opponent's breathing becomes data, the way she learned to read the tremor in a hand hovering over a clock. She is franker than any player I have read on the physicality of it, the weight loss during tournaments, the insomnia, the fear. And she is unsparing about what she calls the game's 'beautiful alibi': the way total dedication to something so obviously demanding excused her, for years, from developing any other self.\n\nIf the memoir has a weakness, it is the middle section covering her decade away from the board, in which she retrains as an architect and, in her telling, learns to be ordinary. These chapters feel thinner, and one senses Kalman knows it; she hurries through years at a pace the earlier chapters would never permit. It may be that ordinariness resists her descriptive gifts, or, less charitably, that she remains most interesting to herself in the vicinity of the sixty-four squares. A stricter editor might have compressed this material further and been thanked for it.\n\nThe final chapters, in which a forty-year-old Kalman enters an open tournament under a false name and finds the old perceptions flooding back, could easily have collapsed into triumphalism. They do not, because Kalman is too honest about what she finds: not that she still loves chess, but that she still fears the person she becomes when she plays it, and has decided, this time with open eyes, to admit that person on strictly limited terms. The title, a chess term for a position in which any move worsens your situation but you are obliged to move, thus becomes something better than a clever flourish. It is the book's whole argument. Kalman's achievement is to show that walking away and going back were, in a sense, the same move, and that the game, like the past, does not release you merely because you have stopped playing. Anyone expecting a manual of openings should look elsewhere. Everyone else should read it.",
