    title: "Accents Reunited: Dialect Returns to the Airwaves",
    text: "My grandmother, who spent her working life in a Lancashire mill town, used to straighten her back slightly when the radio news came on, as though the announcer could see her. The voice from the wireless spoke a variety of English she never heard on her street and never attempted herself, and the lesson she absorbed, without anyone stating it, was that the language of authority was not hers. It is a small, domestic image, but I think of it whenever I hear the current debate about regional dialects in broadcasting, because it is a useful reminder of what the old settlement actually taught people, beneath its talk of clarity and standards.\n\nFor most of the twentieth century, British broadcasting operated on the assumption that one accent, Received Pronunciation, was a neutral instrument and all others were flavours, acceptable in comedy, drama and sport, but unsuited to news, authority and abstraction. The assumption was never linguistically defensible; no accent is inherently clearer than another to those who grow up with it. It was a social arrangement wearing a technical justification, and its effect was to broadcast, alongside the news, a daily message about whose speech counted.\n\nThat settlement has visibly loosened, and lately something more interesting than mere accent diversity has emerged: the deliberate revival of dialect, not just the sounds of a region but its words and constructions, in mainstream programming. A Scots-language news bulletin now runs on a national digital channel. A drama series set in the North East retained its Geordie dialect coaching bill rather than sanding the script into 'television Northern'. Local stations have begun heritage projects pairing elderly speakers with young presenters, explicitly framed as transmission rather than nostalgia. The audience response has confounded the cautious: the Scots bulletin's online clips travel far beyond Scotland, and the drama's international streaming figures suggest subtitled authenticity sells better than diluted accessibility.\n\nPredictably, the development has its critics, and not all of them are snobs. The serious objection is that dialect on air excludes: that a listener in Cornwall should not need subtitles for a programme made in her own country, and that public broadcasters, of all institutions, should maximise intelligibility. I have some sympathy, but the argument smuggles in an assumption worth exposing, namely that intelligibility is a one-way street, that the burden of adjustment falls forever on the regional speaker and never on the listener. Standard-accent broadcasting also excluded; it simply excluded people whose exclusion was not counted. Comprehension, moreover, is trainable. The first week of any unfamiliar dialect is the hardest; ask the global audiences who now happily follow dramas from Naples or Glasgow that their own national broadcasters once deemed too parochial to export.\n\nA more troubling worry, to my mind, comes from within the revival itself. Dialect that returns to the airwaves as performance can become costume: a signifier of grit or warmth deployed by producers, worn thickest in trailers and thinned out when the content turns serious. If regional speech is only ever the voice of drama and never the voice of the six o'clock news, the old hierarchy has not been dismantled, merely redecorated. The test of the revival is not how many accents appear on television but which registers they are permitted to occupy. A Geordie voice narrating a nature documentary is pleasant; a Geordie voice announcing a budget is structural change.\n\nMy grandmother did not live to hear a newsreader who sounded like her neighbours. I do not want to overclaim what it would have meant; she was not waiting for broadcasting's permission to value herself. But institutions teach, whether they intend to or not, and a child in a mill town today who hears her own vowels carrying the day's most serious news is being taught something my grandmother was not. The lesson costs the rest of us nothing more than a week of unfamiliar listening. It seems a reasonable price.",
